orms for consulting with third-parties, regulations for interactions with patients, and medical uncertainty. While at an institutional and individual level patient care continues to be integral to everything the physicians do, they are forced to reconcile that vow with these other, often-conflicting internal logics. Harm, Nelson argues, is thus built into the practice of medicine in the United States. This harm can take the form of unnecessary treatments and consultations or inadequate treatment for pain to motivate specialist intervention that would otherwise be resisted. These and other practices have the overall consequence of significantly driving up inpatient care costs, which then results in patients forgoing needed, ongoing treatment once they receive their medical bills. Drawing on a deep ethnography of physicians in the Internal Medicine Service unit, Nelson offers a sharp assessment of current policies aimed at alleviating medical costs and explains why they are ineffective. She concludes by offering novel policy and practice recommendations for health care practitioners, policy makers, and healthcare institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAcademic medical centerszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aClinical medicinezUnited StatesxDecision makingvCase studies. 0aMedical carezUnited StatesxDecision makingvCase studies. 0aPhysicianszUnited StatesxPsychologyvCase studies. 7aMEDICAL / Education & Training.2bisacsh  acommodification of care.  aethnography.  ahidden curriculum.  alegal risk.  aorganizations.  apatient-doctor interactions.  aphysicians.  aprofessionalization.  asocialization.  astatus hierarchies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363348340uh